(A)	CLIENT SERVER COMMUNICATION USING UDP

ALGRITHM-
Server Side
1.	Start
2.	Set HOST = 127.0.0.1 and PORT = 9999
3.	Create a UDP socket: sock = socket(AF_INET, SOCK_DGRAM)
4.	Bind the socket to (HOST, PORT) so it can receive messages
5.	Display: “UDP Server listening on HOST:PORT”
6.	Repeat forever:
•	Receive a UDP packet using recvfrom(2048) → returns (data, addr)
•	Decode data from bytes to string using UTF-8
•	Print: Received from addr: message
•	Create reply text: "ACK: " + message
•	Encode reply to bytes (UTF-8)
•	Send reply back to the same client address using sendto(reply_bytes, addr)
•	Stop (only if program is manually terminated)

Client Side
1.	Start
2.	Set SERVER_HOST = 127.0.0.1 and SERVER_PORT = 9999
3.	Create a UDP socket: sock = socket(AF_INET, SOCK_DGRAM)
4.	Set receive timeout to 3 seconds: sock.settimeout(3)
5.	Display prompt: “Type messages…”
6.	Repeat forever:
•	Read a message from user: msg = input()
•	Convert message to bytes (UTF-8)
•	Send message to server using sendto(msg_bytes, (SERVER_HOST, SERVER_PORT))
•	Try to receive reply using recvfrom(2048):
	If reply received within 3 sec:
o	Decode reply bytes to text (UTF-8)
o	Print: Server: <reply>
	If timeout occurs:
o	Print: “No response (timeout). Is the server running?”
7.	Stop (only when user terminates program, e.g., Ctrl+C)

